## Authorization Code Flow vs Implicit Flow

### 1. Token Exposure

#### **Implicit Flow**
```javascript
// Implicit flow - tokens in URL fragment
// https://app.example.com/#access_token=eyJhbG...&token_type=Bearer&expires_in=3600

// Automatic token extraction
window.location.hash.split('&').forEach(param => {
  // Token exposed in browser history, referrer headers
});
```

**Security vulnerabilities:**
- **Access tokens appear in URL fragments** - visible in browser history
- **Referrer leakage** - tokens can leak through Referer headers if user navigates away
- **Browser extensions** - malicious extensions can access URL fragments
- **No client authentication** - server cannot verify the requesting application

#### **Authorization Code Flow (with PKCE)**
```javascript
// Step 1: Generate code verifier and challenge
function generateCodeVerifier() {
  const array = new Uint8Array(32);
  crypto.getRandomValues(array);
  return base64URLEncode(array);
}

function generateCodeChallenge(verifier) {
  const encoder = new TextEncoder();
  const data = encoder.encode(verifier);
  return crypto.subtle.digest('SHA-256', data)
    .then(hash => base64URLEncode(new Uint8Array(hash)));
}

// Step 2: Authorization request
const codeVerifier = generateCodeVerifier();
const codeChallenge = await generateCodeChallenge(codeVerifier);

const authUrl = `https://auth.provider.com/authorize?
  response_type=code&
  client_id=${clientId}&
  redirect_uri=${redirectUri}&
  code_challenge=${codeChallenge}&
  code_challenge_method=S256`;

// Step 3: Exchange code for token (backend call)
// Code appears in URL: https://app.example.com/?code=abc123
const response = await fetch('https://auth.provider.com/token', {
  method: 'POST',
  headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/x-www-form-urlencoded' },
  body: new URLSearchParams({
    grant_type: 'authorization_code',
    code: authorizationCode,
    redirect_uri: redirectUri,
    client_id: clientId,
    code_verifier: codeVerifier
  })
});
```

**Security advantages:**
- **Authorization code in URL, not token** - code is single-use and short-lived
- **PKCE prevents interception attacks** - even if code is stolen, attacker cannot exchange it
- **Token exchange happens server-side** - access token never exposed in URL
- **Supports client authentication** - when backend is available

